/gtr:id><gtr:title>ESRC Business Placement Fellows</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-186-27-0010</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>City-regions are under new pressure to more effectively integrate their economic and spatial aspirations with their critical infrastructures of energy, water, waste, mobility and flood protection. Climate change, carbon regulation and resource constraint increasingly demand &amp;quot;systemic&amp;quot; changes in the social and technical organisation of infrastructure networks. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>In response to these challenges city-regions need to develop new forms of knowledge and expertise, as well as the capacity and capability to effect major transitions in their infrastructure. Yet many of the most critical networks are out of city-regions direct control, as they are provided by government agencies or regulated private companies. Consequently knowledge of infrastructures and the capability to shape networks are poorly developed at a time when city-regions need to create and tailor their own frameworks of infrastructural management. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The purpose of this research placement is to identify the key knowledge, expertise and capabilities required to undertake systemic transitions in city-regional infrastructure in ways that can be utilised by ARUP, policy makers and other public and private sector organisations. The resulting framework will outline the critical steps involved in the production of effective organisation and management of infrastructure systems. &lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2008-12-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>20000</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RES">RES-186-27-0010</gtr:identifier><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">RES-186-27-0010</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>E844174D-6A1C-4D2D-8F24-57698F7DA353</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Environmental planning</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>E844174D-6A1C-4D2D-8F24-57698F7DA353</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Environmental planning</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic></gtr:researchTopics><gtr:rcukProgrammes/></gtr:project></gtr:projectComposition></gtr:projectOverview>